SIMPLE: seemly
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seemly
<hw>Seem"ly</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧m"l⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos><adjf>Seemlier</adjf>
<pr>(s⟦emac⟧m"l⟦icr⟧*⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Seeliest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[Icel. <ets>s⟦ae⟧miligr</ets>, fr.
<ets>s⟦ae⟧mr</ets> becoming, fit; akin to <ets>samr</ets> same, E.
<ets>same</ets>; the sense being properly, the same or like, hence,
fitting. See <er>Seem</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>Suited to the
object, occasion, purpose, or character; suitable; fit; becoming;
comely; decorous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had a <qex>seemly</qex> nose.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am a woman, lacking wit⟦br⟧
To make a <qex>seemly</qex> answer to such persons.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Suspense of judgment and exercise of charity were safer and
<qex>seemlier</qex> for Christian men than the hot pursuit of these
controversies.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Becoming; fit; suitable; proper; appropriate;
congruous; meet; decent; decorous.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seemly</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seemly
<hw>Seem"ly</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧m"l⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Seemlier</adjf>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Seemliest</adjf>.]</amorph> <def>In a decent or suitable manner;
becomingly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Suddenly a men before him stood,⟦br⟧
Not rustic as before, but <qex>seemlier</qex> clad,⟦br⟧
As one in city or court or place bred.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seemlyhed</ent>⟦br⟧
